We would like to be able to support multiple choice questions. In Open edX, this was:

<problem>
  <choiceresponse>
    <label>Question or prompt text</label>
    <description>Information about how to answer the question</description>
    <checkboxgroup>
      <choice correct="false">Answer option A (incorrect)</choice>
      <choice correct="true">Answer option B (correct)</choice>
      <choice correct="false">Answer option C (incorrect)</choice>
    </checkboxgroup>
  <solution>
    <div class="detailed-solution">
      <p>Optional header for the explanation or solution</p>
      <p>Optional explanation or solution text</p>
    </div>
  </solution>
  </choiceresponse>
  <demandhint>
    <hint>Hint 1</hint>
    <hint>Hint 2</hint>
  </demandhint>
</problem>

In LON-CAPA:

<radiobuttonresponse direction="vertical" max="10" randomize="yes">
    <foilgroup>
        <foil location="random" value="true" name="foil1">
            <startouttext />Option 1<endouttext />
        </foil>
        <foil location="random" value="false" name="foil2">
            <startouttext />Option 2<endouttext />
        </foil>
        <foil location="random" value="false" name="foil3">
            <startouttext />Option 3<endouttext />
        </foil>
        <foil location="random" value="false" name="foil4">
            <startouttext />Option 4<endouttext />
        </foil>
    </foilgroup>
</radiobuttonresponse>

Perhaps we will use terminology here correctly, though:

<MultipleChoice> <!-- SelectedResponseGrader? I think this is simpler, but it's still a grader -->
   <Stem> What is the second letter of the alphabet?
   <Alternatives>
      <Distractor> Answer option A (incorrect) </Distractor>
      <Key> Answer option B (correct) </Key>
      <Distractor> Answer option C (incorrect) </Distractor>
   </Alternatives>
</MultipleChoice>

I'd make <Alternatives> optional. This should be valid too:

<MultipleChoice> <!-- SelectedResponseGrader? I think this is simpler, but it's still a grader -->
   <Stem> What is the second letter of the alphabet?
   <Distractor> Answer option A (incorrect) </Distractor>
   <Key> Answer option B (correct) </Key>
   <Distractor> Answer option C (incorrect) </Distractor>
</MultipleChoice>

